"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381210","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-23","<p>My rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State has regular meetings with Cabinet colleagues on a variety of topics.</p><p>Details of meetings between Ministers and external organisations are published quarterly on the Departmental website at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/ministers-meeting-with-external-organisations" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/ministers-meeting-with-external-organisations</a>.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","2424 ; 2436 ; 2437 ; 2438","2015-06-23T12:55:35.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381210/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381210/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381210/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-15","Environment Protection: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, when she last met with the Secretary of State for Scotland to discuss the effect of the carbon price floor on Scottish energy security.","false","Biography information for David T. C. Davies","Monmouth","David T. C. Davies","2439"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381211","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-06-22","<p>The costs of the Carbon Price Floor on business are largely indirect, passed through in bills by their electricity supplier. However, the Department for Energy and Climate Change’s Prices and Bills report estimates that in 2014 the Carbon Price Floor increased the price per MWh of electricity for the average uncompensated energy intensive business by £4. The Government pays compensation to the most electricity intensive industries which reduces the price impact for the average compensated energy intensive business in 2014 to £2 per MWh.</p><p>My Department keeps the risk of carbon leakage under regular review.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","2440 ; 2441","2015-06-22T09:41:37.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381211/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381211/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381211/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-06-15","Energy Intensive Industries: Trade Competitiveness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimate he has made of direct costs to the energy intensive industry resulting from the introduction of legislative proposals on a carbon price floor.","false","Biography information for David T. C. Davies","Monmouth","David T. C. Davies","2426"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381212","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-18","<p /> <p>We will set out proposals to deliver on our manifesto commitments on child poverty in due course.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-06-18T10:47:55.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381212/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381212/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381212/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-15","Children: Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether he plans to bring forward legislative proposals to amend the measure of child poverty defined in the Child Poverty Act 2010.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","2420"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381213","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-06-22","<p>The costs of the Carbon Price Floor on business are largely indirect, passed through in bills by their electricity supplier. However, the Department for Energy and Climate Change’s Prices and Bills report estimates that in 2014 the Carbon Price Floor increased the price per MWh of electricity for the average uncompensated energy intensive business by £4. The Government pays compensation to the most electricity intensive industries which reduces the price impact for the average compensated energy intensive business in 2014 to £2 per MWh.</p><p>My Department keeps the risk of carbon leakage under regular review.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","2426 ; 2441","2015-06-22T09:41:37.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381213/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381213/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/381213/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-06-15","Energy Intensive Industries: Trade Competitiveness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, when he last met with representatives of the energy intensive industry to discuss the disparity between (a) UK carbon prices under the carbon price floor and (b) such prices in the rest of Europe.","false","Biography information for David T. C. Davies","Monmouth","David T. C. Davies","2440"
