"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353859","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-19","<p>For the financial year 2013-14 the Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency (DVLA) received £6,052 million from vehicle excise duty and £41 million from fines. Monthly figures are not available.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-06-19T10:04:41.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353859/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353859/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353859/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-12","Motor Vehicles: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much income the DVLA received from vehicle excise duty (a) fees and (b) fines in each month of the most recent year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","2298"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353860","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-22","<p>DECC does not hold data on renewable subsidies broken down to regions or districts.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-06-22T10:12:39.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353860/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353860/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353860/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-12","Renewable Energy: Cumbria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what the cost to the public purse was of renewable subsidies received by businesses in (a) Cumbria, (b) Carlisle District in (i) 2012-13 (ii) 2013-14 and (iii) 2014-15.","false","Biography information for John Stevenson","Carlisle","John Stevenson","2309"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353861","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-23","<p>Onshore wind has made a valuable contribution to the UK energy mix in recent years and we are confident that it will make its expected contribution to the UK’s carbon reduction and renewables targets. We will consider carefully the level of investment that developers are likely to bring forward under the proposals announced by my rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State on 18 June.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-06-23T13:25:02.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353861/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353861/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353861/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-12","Wind Power: Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what estimate her Department has made of the amount invested in onshore wind projects planned to begin before 31 March 2017 which have not yet received Renewables Obligation Certificates.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","2306"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353862","Cabinet Office","false","2015-06-17","<p>Every candidate standing in the General Election must pay a deposit of £500, which is forfeited if they fail to gain five per cent of the vote in the constituency in which they are standing.</p><p>The total amount that is to be returned to the Consolidated Fund as a result of candidates losing their deposit at the 2015 General Election is £773,000. This represents 1,546 candidates that lost their deposit.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose",,"2015-06-17T13:46:38.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353862/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353862/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353862/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-06-12","General Election 2015","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much was accrued to the public purse as a result of candidates losing their deposits at the 2015 General Election.","false","Biography information for Simon Danczuk","Rochdale","Simon Danczuk","2296"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353863","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-17","<p>The development of the policy is ongoing, and details will be set out in due course.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-06-17T14:57:48.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353863/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353863/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353863/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-12","Right to Buy Scheme: Southwark","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the total number of housing association properties in the London Borough of Southwark that would become available to buy under the Government's current proposal to extend the right to buy policy to housing association tenants.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","2292"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353864","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-17","<p /> <p>The information as requested is not available.</p><p> </p><p>The Information for those in work is only available for Housing Benefit (HB) recipients whose claim is not passported: that is for those who do not receive either income support, Jobseeker’s Allowance (Income-Based), Employment and Support Allowance (Income-Based), or Pension Credit (Guaranteed Credit). This information can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk</a></p><p>Guidance on how to extract the information required can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started---SuperWEB2.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started---SuperWEB2.html</a></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-06-17T12:18:45.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353864/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353864/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353864/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-12","Housing Benefit: Southwark","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many households with one or more person employed in the London Borough of Southwark claim housing benefit.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","2293"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353865","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-17","<p>Benefit cap statistics for February 2015, published in May 2015 (the latest available information) can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/benefit-cap-number-of-households-capped-to-february-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/benefit-cap-number-of-households-capped-to-february-2015</a></p><p> </p><p>The number of households subject to the benefit cap in the London Borough of Southwark in February, was 210. Of those households:</p><p>a) 160 were single parent households.</p><p>b) 200 households had dependent children.</p><p>c) Households with someone in receipt of the following disability related benefits are exempt from the cap - Attendance Allowance, Disability Living Allowance and its replacement Personal Independence Payment (PIP), Employment and Support Allowance where the support component has been awarded, Industrial Injuries Benefits (IIB), Armed Forces Compensation Scheme (AFCS) (Guaranteed Income Payments) and, before 6 April 2005, the War Pension Scheme (WPS) (this includes war widow's/widower's pension and war disablement pension).</p><p>d) None. The benefit cap applies to working-age households.</p><p>e) Households with one or more persons employed and entitled to Working Tax Credit are exempt from the cap.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-06-17T14:10:33.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353865/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353865/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353865/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-12","Social Security Benefits: Southwark","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many (a) single parent households, (b) households with dependent children, (c) households with a disabled member, (d) pensioner households and (e) households with one or more person employed in the London Borough of Southwark are subject to the benefit cap.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","2294"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353866","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-17","<p /> <p>The number of households that have been subject to the benefit cap from its introduction on 15 April 2013, until February 2015, the latest available information, in the Local Authority of Southwark is 450.</p><p> </p><p>The data has been taken from Stat-Xplore, the Department’s online interactive tabulation tool, which can be accessed here:</p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/</a></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-06-17T12:23:33.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353866/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353866/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353866/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-12","Social Security Benefits: Southwark","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many households in the London Borough of Southwark have been subject to the benefit cap.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","2295"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353867","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-18","<p>As promised in our manifesto, we have committed to planting 11 million trees during this Parliament, which we plan to do primarily through the Rural Development Programme’s Countryside Stewardship scheme. This scheme aims to invest £18 million on new woodland planting each year.</p><p> </p><p>We are also encouraging more woodland creation in several other ways. For example, our Woodland Carbon Code continues to attract private investment in woodland creation projects. The Forestry Commission is also leading an Environmental Impact Assessment project in Durham to help give clarity to landowners on where a full Environmental Statement may be required for afforestation, which may be deterring some landowners from planting new woodland. We will also help increase demand for wood by supporting forestry businesses to further increase their competitiveness, productivity and innovation, through other schemes under the Rural Development Programme.</p><p> </p><p>We remain strongly supportive of sector-led initiatives, such as Grown in Britain and the Roots to Prosperity strategy, in their work to grow demand for wood by further developing and strengthening the woodland economy from ground level up.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-06-18T15:10:48.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353867/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353867/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353867/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-12","Forests","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans she has to accelerate the rate of new woodland planting.","false","Biography information for Neil Parish","Tiverton and Honiton","Neil Parish","2316"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353868","Department of Health","false","2015-06-22","<p>Local authorities have been provided with £470 million in total for the cost of the new duties in the Care Act 2014 which came into effect in April 2015 and to support them in preparing for the reforms planned for April 2016. The process for assessing the costs was comprehensive and fully involved local government. The new burdens identified have been fully funded.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The National Audit Office (NAO) considered the Department’s approach to supporting delivery of the Care Act reforms, and concluded that this “has been implemented well, and shows good practice from which other programmes could learn.”</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In relation to the process of assessing potential costs, the NAO’s report recognises the inherent difficulty of estimating demand, since this is dependent on individual behaviour. As a result, the NAO recognises that the Department’s estimate of the costs of the new rights for carers is based on an assumption that is “as reasonable” (paragraph 3.10) as that of NAO.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department has consistently acknowledged the difficulty of estimating these costs precisely, and undertook a cost modelling exercise with around 120 local authorities to review its assumptions. Following that work, the Department agreed with the Association of Directors of Adult Social Services and the Local Government Association a process for the ongoing monitoring of specified demand data in all local authorities from 1 April 2015, based on the areas of most significant risk as identified by local authorities.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The new data collection covers the new burdens from the Care Act 2014 related to carers’ rights, the national minimum eligibility threshold, assessments for self-funders, deferred payment agreements, care and support in prisons, new rights to advocacy and safeguarding. It is being collected quarterly from 1 April 2015 as part of the regular Care Act implementation stocktakes of local authorities and will be reported to the Care and Support Reform Programme Board. It will help local government, in partnership with the Department, to understand whether the demand experienced is consistent with the assumptions made, and to consider cases where additional targeted support may be required.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department continues to work directly with local authorities and partners to support effective and efficient implementation, building on the additional £30 million investment support implementation provided in the 2014/15 year.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","2331","2015-06-22T13:46:20.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353868/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353868/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353868/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-12","Carers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the implications for his policies of the findings of the National Audit Office in its report on the Care Act first-phase reforms, published in June 2015, on potential underestimation of demand for assessments and services for carers equating to a rise of £27 million in extra assessments and services.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","2326"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353869","Department of Health","false","2015-06-22","<p>Local authorities have been provided with £470 million in total for the cost of the new duties in the Care Act 2014 which came into effect in April 2015 and to support them in preparing for the reforms planned for April 2016. The process for assessing the costs was comprehensive and fully involved local government. The new burdens identified have been fully funded.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The National Audit Office (NAO) considered the Department’s approach to supporting delivery of the Care Act reforms, and concluded that this “has been implemented well, and shows good practice from which other programmes could learn.”</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In relation to the process of assessing potential costs, the NAO’s report recognises the inherent difficulty of estimating demand, since this is dependent on individual behaviour. As a result, the NAO recognises that the Department’s estimate of the costs of the new rights for carers is based on an assumption that is “as reasonable” (paragraph 3.10) as that of NAO.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department has consistently acknowledged the difficulty of estimating these costs precisely, and undertook a cost modelling exercise with around 120 local authorities to review its assumptions. Following that work, the Department agreed with the Association of Directors of Adult Social Services and the Local Government Association a process for the ongoing monitoring of specified demand data in all local authorities from 1 April 2015, based on the areas of most significant risk as identified by local authorities.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The new data collection covers the new burdens from the Care Act 2014 related to carers’ rights, the national minimum eligibility threshold, assessments for self-funders, deferred payment agreements, care and support in prisons, new rights to advocacy and safeguarding. It is being collected quarterly from 1 April 2015 as part of the regular Care Act implementation stocktakes of local authorities and will be reported to the Care and Support Reform Programme Board. It will help local government, in partnership with the Department, to understand whether the demand experienced is consistent with the assumptions made, and to consider cases where additional targeted support may be required.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department continues to work directly with local authorities and partners to support effective and efficient implementation, building on the additional £30 million investment support implementation provided in the 2014/15 year.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","2326","2015-06-22T13:46:18.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353869/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353869/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353869/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-12","Local Government Services: Carers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how his Department plans to monitor the costs to local authorities of the Care Act 2014; and if he will make it his policy to provide additional funding to the councils which experience increased demand for their services.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","2331"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353870","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-18","<p>The Treasury does not hold any information on the proportions of interest-only mortgages and capital repayment mortgages for residential properties or buy-to-let.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The FCA in conjunction with the Bank of England publish the Mortgage Lenders and Administrators Return (MLAR) statistics quarterly. In their most recent MLAR (Quarter 1 2015) interest-only mortgages accounted for 8.61 per cent of all regulated residential mortgages.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The latest report (which has data back to 2007) can be found in the following link: <em>www.bankofengland.co.uk/pra/Documents/regulatorydata/mlar/2015/q1longrundetailed.xls </em></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>There is no data separating the proportion of interest-only mortgages and capital repayment mortgages within buy-to-let.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","2347","2015-06-18T12:07:55.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353870/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353870/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353870/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-12","Mortgages","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what information he holds on the proportion of residential mortgage lending that was on (a) an interest-only and (b) a capital repayment basis in each year since 1997.","true","Biography information for James Cartlidge","South Suffolk","James Cartlidge","2346"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353871","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-18","<p>The Treasury does not hold any information on the proportions of interest-only mortgages and capital repayment mortgages for residential properties or buy-to-let.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The FCA in conjunction with the Bank of England publish the Mortgage Lenders and Administrators Return (MLAR) statistics quarterly. In their most recent MLAR (Quarter 1 2015) interest-only mortgages accounted for 8.61 per cent of all regulated residential mortgages.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The latest report (which has data back to 2007) can be found in the following link: <em>www.bankofengland.co.uk/pra/Documents/regulatorydata/mlar/2015/q1longrundetailed.xls </em></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>There is no data separating the proportion of interest-only mortgages and capital repayment mortgages within buy-to-let.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","2346","2015-06-18T12:07:55.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353871/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353871/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353871/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-12","Mortgages","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what information he holds on the proportion of buy-to-let mortgage lending that was on (a) an interest-only and (b) a capital repayment basis in each year since 1997.","false","Biography information for James Cartlidge","South Suffolk","James Cartlidge","2347"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353872","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-22","<p>The Government's strategy for city centres is to work with the commercial suppliers to encourage them to deploy superfast and ultrafast broadband quickly to as many premises as possible, for example it has prequalified the expansion of Virgin Media’s ultrafast broadband network for the UK Guarantees Scheme, supporting Virgin’s proposed £3 billion investment.</p><p> </p><p>We are also providing direct financial support to small and medium sized businesses in 50 cities across the UK through the Broadband Connection Voucher Scheme, which contributes up to £3,000 to each SME to help pay for the connection costs to faster and better broadband.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-06-22T16:05:34.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353872/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353872/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353872/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-12","Broadband: Urban Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps he is taking to resolve non-spots in urban areas as part of the superfast broadband roll-out.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","2333"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353873","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-17","<p>As at 15 June 2015, the total of 867,897 penalty charge notices have been issued for non-payment of the Dart Charge following its introduction on 30<sup>th</sup> November 2014.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-06-17T11:29:04.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353873/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353873/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353873/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-12","Dartford-Thurrock Crossing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many penalty charge notices for non-payment of the Dart Charge have been issued for since free-flow charging was introduced at the Dartford Crossing.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","2342"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353874","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-17","<p>As at 15 June 151,871 Penalty Charge Notices have been passed to our European Debt Recovery Agency (EDRA) for issue to non-UK drivers.</p><p> </p><p>Currently 143,633 of these remain unpaid. Recovery of charges from overseas can be a lengthy process, as it can take several months to secure registered keeper details.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-06-17T11:32:18.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353874/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353874/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353874/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-12","Dartford-Thurrock Crossing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many penalty charge notices for non-payment of the Dart Charge issued since free-flow charging was introduced (a) have been in respect of foreign-registered vehicles and (b) remain unpaid.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","2343"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353875","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-17","<p>The Government will implement the requirements of the Directive by 7 May 2017.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-06-17T11:35:22.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353875/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353875/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353875/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-12","Road Traffic Offences: Fines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether the Government plans to implement the EU Cross-Border Enforcement Directive in respect of non-payment of fines.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","2344"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353876","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-16","<p>Through the Waste and Resources Action Programme the Government is working with food manufacturers and retailers, including all the major UK supermarkets, to meet targets to reduce food waste from households and the grocery supply chain under the Courtauld Commitment.</p><p>Signatories reported a reduction of 7.4% in food supply chain waste since 2010 (there are also targets on household food waste and packaging waste). The third phase targets a further 1.1 million tonnes of food and packaging waste reduction by the end of 2015.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-06-16T16:41:37.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353876/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353876/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353876/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-12","Food: Waste","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps she is taking to tackle food waste in supermarkets.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","2313"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353877","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-17","<p /> <p>This Government is committed to driving real change in children’s lives, by tackling the root causes of poverty such as entrenched worklessness, family breakdown, problem debt, and drug and alcohol dependency.</p><p> </p><p>There are 300,000 fewer children living in relative poverty since 2010. We know that work is the best route out of poverty and the number of children growing up in workless families is at a record low. As a result of the introduction of Universal Credit, we estimate around 3.2 million households across the UK will be better off and up to 300,000 more people will enter work due to improved financial incentives. We are doubling the amount of free childcare to 30 hours of childcare for working parents of 3 and 4 year olds, making it easier for them to go back to work.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-06-17T14:50:39.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353877/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353877/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353877/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-12","Children: Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps he is taking to ensure that the Government meets its commitment to eradicate child poverty by 2020.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","2352"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353878","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-17","<p>Care leavers on low incomes will be entitled to support under local council tax support schemes. They may also be entitled to existing council tax discounts or exemptions, for example by virtue of being students or single occupiers. Local authorities have broad discretion to grant discounts to individuals or groups in other circumstances, and they may wish to consider providing support specifically to care leavers.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2015-06-17T14:58:52.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353878/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353878/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353878/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-12","Care Leavers: Council Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will put in place support to assist care leavers with the payment of council tax.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","2353"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353879","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-17","<p>All Jobcentre Plus staff have access to a comprehensive and progressive learning programme designed to build the core skills and knowledge essential to the role. This learning encompasses the wide range of circumstances that our claimants may have, some less obvious than others, and stresses how important it is to treat people as individuals.</p><p> </p><p>Specific features of the learning include the skills required to coach claimants in navigating what is required to find, gain and sustain employment, in an increasingly digital environment.</p><p> </p><p>Work Coaches in particular are trained to have an understanding of local labour market information, using various tools to support claimants into work and training. Work Coaches can also signpost claimants to the National Careers Service, Careers Scotland and Careers Wales as required.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-06-17T12:31:09.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353879/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353879/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353879/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-12","Jobcentre Plus","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many Jobcentre Plus staff have received training in careers advice and guidance since May 2010.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","2370"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353880","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-22","<p>Following the review of PFI in 2012 and the launch of PF2, there are no new PFI projects being negotiated across central government.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-06-22T15:45:40.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353880/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353880/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353880/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-12","Central Government: Private Finance Initiative","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many PFI contracts are being negotiated across central government.","false","Biography information for Dame Margaret Hodge","Barking","Margaret Hodge","2360"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353881","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-19","<p>The information requested is publically available and is accessible at the following link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/private-finance-initiative-projects-2014-summary-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/private-finance-initiative-projects-2014-summary-data</a>.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","2359","2015-06-19T13:19:04.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353881/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353881/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353881/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-12","Central Government: Private Finance Initiative","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many PFI projects across central government were signed off in each year from 2010 to 2015; what the values of those contracts were; and what those contracts were for.","false","Biography information for Dame Margaret Hodge","Barking","Margaret Hodge","2361"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353882","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-19","<p>The information requested is publically available and is accessible at the following link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/private-finance-initiative-projects-2014-summary-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/private-finance-initiative-projects-2014-summary-data</a>.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","2361","2015-06-19T13:19:04.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353882/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353882/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353882/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-12","Private Finance Initiative","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many PFI contracts were negotiated by (a) NHS trusts, (b) Academy trusts and (c) local authorities in each year from 2010 to 2015; what the values of those contracts were; and what those contracts were for.","false","Biography information for Dame Margaret Hodge","Barking","Margaret Hodge","2359"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353883","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-19","<p>Services between Telford and Birmingham are supplied by more than one operator; London Midland and Arriva Trains Wales. Their Franchise Agreements state the minimum service provision of the train operator to protect service provision for passengers. This sees both providing hourly services Monday to Friday and where reasonable, these shall be timed with the other operator to promote a half hourly service.</p><p> </p><p>Whilst the train operators cannot run fewer services than are stipulated (nor simply remove a station stop or two as this could mean that the minimum specifications for those removed station stops are not met), if the train operators believe that the demand exists for additional services (which may have quicker journey times) and they have the rolling stock, staff availability and they can obtain the required track access rights, there is nothing to stop them from running more frequent services. My Hon Friend, may wish to contact the operators to explore what options may be available to achieve quicker journeys in the short-term*.</p><p>Local Councils can also help specify and fund transport solutions if they decide that this is the best way to meet local transport needs. In doing so, they would discuss the feasibility of the scheme with Network Rail and the train operator(s). If the scheme is feasible and represents value for money, the Council would need to be prepared to fund the cost from sources which are available for transport investment.</p><p>The Department is aware of stakeholder aspirations for improvements in and to the service provision between Telford and Birmingham. As part of the competition for the new long term franchises for this route, public consultations will be opened to help inform the specification for those franchises.</p><p> </p><p>*Arriva Trains Wales contact email:<a href="mailto:customer.relations@arrivatrainswales.co.uk" target="_blank">customer.relations@arrivatrainswales.co.uk</a>; London Midland contact email: <a href="http://www.londonmidland.com/contact/contact-us/contact-form/" target="_blank">http://www.londonmidland.com/contact/contact-us/contact-form/</a></p><p> </p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-06-19T09:34:55.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353883/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353883/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353883/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-12","Railways: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will take steps to improve the frequency and speed of rail services between Telford and Birmingham.","false","Biography information for Lucy Allan","Telford","Lucy Allan","2356"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353884","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-17","<p>Information on the average cost of homes sold to first time buyers under Help to Buy is not currently published. However figures are available on the average cost of all homes sold under the Help to Buy: Mortgage Guarantee scheme for England (£163,921). Available figures for the Help to Buy: Equity Loan scheme show the average cost of all homes was £212,932 in England.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-06-17T14:56:54.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353884/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353884/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353884/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-12","Help to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the average cost of properties sold to first-time buyers under the Help to Buy scheme in (a) England, (b) East Midlands and (c) Ashfield.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","2345"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353885","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-17","<p>Statistics on annual Right to Buy sales for each local authority district in England are published in the Department’s Live Table 685 which is available at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-social-housing-sales" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-social-housing-sales</a><br><br>Quarterly data for 2014/15 for each local authority district in England will be published in Live Table 691 on 25 June 2015.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-06-17T15:00:04.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353885/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353885/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353885/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-12","Right to Buy Scheme: Ashfield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many properties were bought in Ashfield under the Right-to-Buy Scheme in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","2348"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353886","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-18","<p> </p><p /> <p>Flood Re is on schedule to be established and begin its operational testing phase by July 2015. It will be a matter for the Flood Re team itself to determine when the scheme is ready to accept policies following authorisation by the Prudential Regulation Authority and the Financial Conduct Authority. We understand that the Flood Re team expect this to be in April 2016.</p><p /> <p>Insurers have agreed to continue to abide by the Statement of Principles which ensures continued access to flood insurance until Flood Re is fully operational.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Insurers have agreed to continue to abide by the Statement of Principles which ensures continued access to flood insurance until Flood Re is fully operational.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-06-18T15:01:17.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353886/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353886/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353886/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-12","Floods: Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, by what date she plans that the flood reinsurance scheme will be fully operational.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","2310"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353887","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-22","<p>The Government protects bees by ensuring that policy actions on pesticides (plant protection products) are based on the best evidence available. Guidance documents for plant protection products are prepared by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA), as the Commission’s independent scientific adviser. They are adopted by the Commission once they have been formally ‘noted’ by Member States in the EU Standing Committee on Plants, Animals, Food and Feed.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>EFSA prepared a new <em>Guidance Document on the risk assessment of plant protection products on bees</em>. When this was put to the Standing Committee in July 2014, it was supported by too few Member States to be ‘noted’. The Commission is still considering the way forward.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Guidance documents for plant protection products are addressed to regulators and regulated companies. They are not statutory and are not incorporated into UK legislation. The Health and Safety Executive, as the UK regulator, and the Expert Committee on Pesticides, which provides independent advice to Ministers, draw on guidance documents in carrying out their work.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","2312","2015-06-22T14:57:07.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353887/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353887/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353887/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-12","Pesticides: Bees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what her policy is on the adoption by the European Commission of the proposed European Food Safety Authority guidance on the risk assessment of plant protection products on bees, published by that organisation in June 2013.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","2311"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353888","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-22","<p>The Government protects bees by ensuring that policy actions on pesticides (plant protection products) are based on the best evidence available. Guidance documents for plant protection products are prepared by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA), as the Commission’s independent scientific adviser. They are adopted by the Commission once they have been formally ‘noted’ by Member States in the EU Standing Committee on Plants, Animals, Food and Feed.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>EFSA prepared a new <em>Guidance Document on the risk assessment of plant protection products on bees</em>. When this was put to the Standing Committee in July 2014, it was supported by too few Member States to be ‘noted’. The Commission is still considering the way forward.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Guidance documents for plant protection products are addressed to regulators and regulated companies. They are not statutory and are not incorporated into UK legislation. The Health and Safety Executive, as the UK regulator, and the Expert Committee on Pesticides, which provides independent advice to Ministers, draw on guidance documents in carrying out their work.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","2311","2015-06-22T14:57:07.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353888/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353888/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353888/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-12","Pesticides: Bees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, by what process and on what timescale she plans to bring forward legislative proposals to incorporate new European Food Safety Authority guidance on the risk assessment of plant protection products on bees into UK pesticides legislation.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","2312"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353889","Department for Transport","true","2015-06-17","<p><del class="ministerial">The Department for Transport ran a public consultation to help inform the specification for the new Northern and TransPennine Express franchises, and received over 21,000 responses; a summary of these have been published on the Government’s website.</del></p><p> </p><p><del class="ministerial">The Invitation To Tender for the Northern franchise has specified the replacement of Pacers (which are currently used) on services between Huddersfield and Sheffield) by the start of 2020, and other rolling stock used on the franchise will be subject to a substantial refurbishment. It also specifies an increase in the Sunday service provision on this route by December 2017. Our process for evaluating franchise bids encourages bidders to exceed the minimum specifications we state, and the bids themselves are due in to the Department by 26 June. We are due to announce the outcome towards the end of the year.</del></p><p><ins class="ministerial">The number of publicly-funded chargepoints for electric vehicles that have been delivered in each of the last 10 years, including those for domestic use and those that are publicly accessible, is provided below. The first Government funding for chargepoints was in 2010/11 under the Coalition Government. Chargepoint installations in 2015/16 will depend on demand for domestic chargepoints and the detail of new infrastructure schemes to be announced later this year. </ins></p><p><ins class="ministerial"> <p> </p><p> </p></ins></p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><ins class="ministerial"> </ins><p><ins class="ministerial"><strong>2010/11</strong></ins></p></td><td><ins class="ministerial"> </ins><p><ins class="ministerial"><strong>2011/12</strong></ins></p></td><td><ins class="ministerial"> </ins><p><ins class="ministerial"><strong>2012/13</strong></ins></p></td><td><ins class="ministerial"> </ins><p><ins class="ministerial"><