"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353893","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-17","<p>Revised air quality plans for nitrogen dioxide will be published by the end of 2015. A 40 day public consultation on draft plans will be held later this year.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to complying in the shortest possible time with limit values for nitrogen dioxide under the Air Quality Directive. The consultation will set out our projected dates for UK compliance.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","2350","2015-06-17T08:41:01.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353893/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353893/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353893/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-12","Air Pollution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, by what date she plans to publish a new consultation on air quality.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","2349"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353894","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-17","<p>Revised air quality plans for nitrogen dioxide will be published by the end of 2015. A 40 day public consultation on draft plans will be held later this year.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to complying in the shortest possible time with limit values for nitrogen dioxide under the Air Quality Directive. The consultation will set out our projected dates for UK compliance.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","2349","2015-06-17T08:41:01.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353894/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353894/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353894/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-12","Air Pollution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, by what date she plans to publish a new national air quality plan.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","2350"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353895","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-16","<p>Revised air quality plans for nitrogen dioxide will be published by the end of 2015. A 40 day public consultation on draft plans will be held later this year.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to complying in the shortest possible time with limit values for nitrogen dioxide under the Air Quality Directive. The consultation will set out our projected dates for UK compliance.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-06-16T16:55:12.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353895/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353895/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353895/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-12","Air Pollution: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, by what date she expects the UK to be compliant with the Air Quality Directive.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","2362"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353896","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-18","<p>All information on historical funding and spending for Flood and Coastal Erosion Risk Management (FCERM) can be found on the GOV.UK website at: <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/401305/Central_Government_Funding_for_Flood_and_Coastal_Erosion_Risk_Management_in_England_feb_2015.pdf" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/401305/Central_Government_Funding_for_Flood_and_Coastal_Erosion_Risk_Management_in_England_feb_2015.pdf</a>.</p><p>All Government funding for FCERM has to be used in the year it is allocated. Defra accrued no surpluses or deficits during the period as all funding provided was used.</p><p>Details of spend for the financial year 2014/15 cannot be provided until Defra’s Annual Report and Accounts have been signed off and laid before Parliament.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-06-18T15:23:33.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353896/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353896/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353896/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-12","Flood Control: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what the (a) budget, (b) outturn and (c) end-of-year surplus was for flood and coastal risk management in her Department in each year from 2010-11 to 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","2365"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353897","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-18","<p>The table below shows the budget for asset maintenance activities for each year from 2010/11 to 2014/15. The actual spend on asset maintenance is in line with the budget for each year, excluding 2014/15. Information on actual spending for the final year cannot be confirmed until the Environment Agency’s Annual Report and Accounts have been signed off and laid before Parliament.</p><p>The figure for 2014/15 includes the additional maintenance funding provided by Defra in the wake of flooding over winter 2013/14.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Financial Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total (£M)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2010/11</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>168</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2011/12</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>156</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2012/13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>170</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2013/14</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>147</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2014/15</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>171</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-06-18T15:29:05.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353897/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353897/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353897/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-12","Flood Control: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what the (a) budget, (b) outturn and (c) end-of-year surplus was for flood asset maintenance in her Department in each year from 2010-11 to 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","2366"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353898","Department for Transport","true","2015-06-17","<p>The Department for Transport ran a public consultation to help inform the specification for the new Northern and TransPennine Express franchises, and received over 21,000 responses; a summary of these have been published on the Government’s website.</p><p> </p><p>The Invitation To Tender for the Northern franchise has specified the replacement of Pacers (which are currently used) on services between Huddersfield and Sheffield) by the start of 2020, and other rolling stock used on the franchise will be subject to a substantial refurbishment. It also specifies an increase in the Sunday service provision on this route by December 2017. Our process for evaluating franchise bids encourages bidders to exceed the minimum specifications we state, and the bids themselves are due in to the Department by 26 June. We are due to announce the outcome towards the end of the year.</p><p> </p><p><ins class="ministerial"> <p><ins class="ministerial">This quesiton was inadvertently grouped with question 2332.</ins></p><p><br /></p></ins></p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-06-17T13:47:08.2Z","2015-06-19T11:17:39.477Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353898/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353898/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353898/answer","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353898/answer/previousversion/5725","Biography information for Andrew Jones","27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-12","Railways: Yorkshire and the Humber","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans he has to improve rail links between Huddersfield and Sheffield.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","2324"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353899","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-22","<p>Last year this Department received around a thousand communications from Guide Dogs campaigners in support of two Private Members’ Bills on pavement parking.</p><p> </p><p>Departmental officials have had contact with Guide Dogs and Living Streets over the last year, to discuss pavement parking.</p><p> </p><p>I also attended the Guide Dogs parliamentary reception in June.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-06-22T10:50:33.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353899/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353899/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353899/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-12","Parking: Pedestrian Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what representations he has received on the Streets Ahead campaign on pavement parking.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","2335"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353900","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-17","<p>The Department for Transport ran a public consultation to help inform the specification for the new Northern and TransPennine Express franchises, and received over 21,000 responses; a summary of these have been published on the Government’s website.</p><p> </p><p>The Invitation To Tender for the Northern franchise has specified the replacement of Pacers (which are currently used) on services between Huddersfield and Sheffield) by the start of 2020, and other rolling stock used on the franchise will be subject to a substantial refurbishment.　 It also specifies an increase in the Sunday service provision on this route by December 2017. Our process for evaluating franchise bids encourages bidders to exceed the minimum specifications we state, and the bids themselves are due in to the Department by 26 June. 　We are due to announce the outcome towards the end of the year.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-06-17T14:31:07.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353900/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353900/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353900/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-12","Railways: Yorkshire and the Humber","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what representations he has received on improving rail links between Huddersfield and other cities and towns in South Yorkshire.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","2322"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353901","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-17","<p>Rail links to and from Huddersfield will benefit from the investment the Government is already making in the North of England rail network in support of its vision of a Northern Powerhouse. The Government has committed to the Northern Hub and electrification programmes, and capacity improvements at Huddersfield station. The new East Coast franchise awarded in November 2014 will lead to Huddersfield being introduced as a new destination for Intercity East Coast services with one service to and from London per day from 2019. The Government has also required bidders for the new Northern and TransPennine Express franchises to replace outdated trains, add a third more capacity and invest in stations. In addition the Leeds City Region Local Enterprise Partnership (LEP) has been provisionally allocated over £780m of Government Growth Deal funding over 20 years towards the West Yorkshire Combined Authority’s multimodal West Yorkshire plus Transport Fund, from which priorities for local transport investment will be determined.</p><p> </p><p>The Government established Transport for the North (TfN) last year to formalise cooperation with Northern City Regions and LEPs on transport issues in the North. The aim is for TfN to speak with one voice to Government on the transport priorities for the whole of the North. The Department is working closely with TfN and Rail North to develop and prioritise the rail options so that the first tranche is ready for consideration as part of the Government’s Rail Investment Strategy for the next rail investment period (CP6, 2019 – 2024). The Government is providing TfN with a development budget of up to £12.5m in 2015/16 to support its wider strategy development work.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-06-17T14:10:50.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353901/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353901/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353901/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-12","Railways: Huddersfield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what funds the Government has set aside from (a) the Northern Powerhouse funding and (b) his Department's funding to improve rail links to and from Huddersfield.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","2323"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353902","Prime Minister","false","2015-06-17","<p>I appointed Sir Nigel Sheinwald as my Special Envoy to engage with Communication Service Providers and other Governments to identify ways of improving intelligence and law enforcement data sharing between different jurisdictions. Sir Nigel has provided me with regular advice on his progress, and the Government will feed this into the work we are taking forward around investigatory powers, following David Anderson QC's recent report.</p>","Witney","Mr David Cameron",,"2015-06-17T13:58:16.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353902/answer","Biography information for Mr David Cameron","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353902/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353902/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2015-06-12","Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, if he will declassify and publish the recent report, produced by Sir Nigel Sheinwald on data sharing.","false","Biography information for Mr David Davis","Haltemprice and Howden","Mr David Davis","2372"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353903","Department for Education","false","2015-06-17","<p>We expect academy trusts to manage their finances appropriately and in accordance with their funding agreement. The Department for Education and Education Funding Agency have considered a range of representations, including from academy trusts, on projected budget deficits in academies. Where appropriate, support will be provided.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2015-06-17T14:38:34.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353903/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353903/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353903/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-12","Academies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent representations she has received on projected budget deficits in academies.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","2336"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353904","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-06-17","<p>This Government takes recovery and enforcement of financial impositions very seriously and remains committed to finding new ways to ensure impositions are paid and to trace those who do not pay. This is why there has been a year on year increase in the total amount of financial penalties collected over the last three years. The amount of money collected has risen from £259m at the end of 2009/10 to an all time high of £290 million at the end of 2013/14 and collections continue to rise. In 2013/14 the total outstanding balance of financial impositions reduced by £26.7m (5%) in the year.</p><p> </p><p>The table below shows the value of financial impositions outstanding as at the end of December 2014 in Nottinghamshire. The figures for the 2014/15 financial year will be available on 25 June 2015.</p><p> </p><p>The outstanding balance figure includes the value of accounts that were not due to be paid by the end of the period specified (either because they were imposed close to the end of the year or because they had payment timescales set by the courts for beyond the end of the year) and those that were being paid by instalments on agreed payment plans. This figure include fines, compensation orders, victim surcharge orders and prosecution costs orders.</p><p> </p><table><thead><tr><td><p><strong>Area</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Outstanding balance as at end of December 2014</strong></p></td></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><p>Nottinghamshire</p></td><td><p>£7,610,378</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2015-06-17T16:38:03.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353904/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353904/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353904/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-12","Unpaid Fines: Nottinghamshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much in outstanding fines there were at courts in Nottinghamshire on (a) 31 March and (b) the last date for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","2289"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353905","Attorney General","false","2015-06-17","<p>The Serious Fraud Office has issued its first letters of invitation but it would not be appropriate to confirm numbers.</p><p>The process of reaching Deferred Prosecution Agreements (DPAs) happens in stages. Initial negotiations are confidential to encourage openness on the part of the company. Under the Criminal Procedure Rules, the Court determines whether any relevant hearings are heard in public or in private. Any DPA must be approved by a judge and publicised.</p><p> </p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2015-06-17T10:11:11.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353905/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353905/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353905/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2015-06-12","Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many letters of invitation to companies to enter negotiations for a deferred prosecution agreement the Serious Fraud Office has issued.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","2337"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353906","Cabinet Office","false","2015-06-17","<p>The UK Anti-Corruption Plan, published in December 2014, stated that Cabinet Office will take forward a review of the enforcement response to bribery and corruption more broadly, reporting to the Inter-Ministerial Group on Anti-Corruption (IMG) by June 2015.</p><p> </p>","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin",,"2015-06-17T10:49:03.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353906/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353906/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353906/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-06-12","Corruption","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to Action 39 of the UK Anti-Corruption Plan, published in December 2014, when the proposed review of the enforcement response to bribery and corruption will be published.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","2354"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353907","Home Office","false","2015-06-17","<p>The National Crime Agency's (NCA) new International Corruption Unit will create a single UK centre of excellence within the NCA for dealing with international bribery and corruption. It brings together resources from the Metropolitan Police Service, the City of London Police and the NCA.</p><p>Officers joining the new unit are bringing their expertise and specialisms, including financial investigation, data analysis and intelligence development. The recruitment of additional investigators and other specialists is under way and the unit also has the ability to draw on the wider skills and capabilities of the NCA.</p><p>The Cabinet Office is currently undertaking a wider review of the enforcement response to bribery and corruption.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-06-17T14:32:38.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353907/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353907/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353907/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-12","National Crime Agency: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to Action 38 of the UK Anti-Corruption Plan, published in December 2014, what steps she has taken to recruit and retain specialists to support corruption investigations in the National Crime Agency; and what skills specialists so recruited have.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","2355"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353908","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-06-17","<p>The Coalition government legislated for secure colleges and we are now considering the next steps. We remain clear that education should be at the very heart of youth custody.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-06-17T14:12:23.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353908/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353908/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353908/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-12","Secure Colleges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when he expects construction to begin on the proposed Secure College.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","2288"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353909","Cabinet Office","false","2015-06-18","<p>It is the responsibility of local authorities to decide how to allocate funding for youth services, according to local need. There is an existing statutory duty on local authorities through Education Act 2006 (Section 507B) to secure, as far as is practicable, sufficient services and activities to improve the wellbeing of young people.</p><p>We continue to offer practical support to the youth sector by promoting innovative delivery models for youth services and supporting organisations to measure their impact and demonstrate their value.</p><p> </p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2015-06-18T12:47:50.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353909/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353909/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353909/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-06-12","Youth Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps he is taking to ensure that local authority-funded youth services are maintained at their current level.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","2300"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353910","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-22","<p>The introduction of business rates retention gives all local authorities a strong incentive to pursue local growth policies, by allowing them to keep a share of the additional business rate income generated by that growth. 94% of authorities expect to see additional business rates income in 2015-16 worth an extra £544 million.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2015-06-22T15:18:50.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353910/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353910/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353910/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-12","Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of devolving business rate retention powers to local authorities.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","2301"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353911","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-22","<p>The Government is clear that it is open to discussing devolution proposals from all places, including towns and counties.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2015-06-22T16:28:46.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353911/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353911/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353911/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-12","Local Government: Devolution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will meet town and county local authority leaders to discuss his Department's policy on devolution of powers.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","2302"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353912","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-22","<p>My Department has received representations from or on behalf of numerous town and county authorities to discuss policy on devolution and to bring forward proposals for the devolution of powers. I welcome these representations and encourage proposals from all areas which would welcome increased powers and greater freedoms to maximise their economic growth, where the case can be made that there is both strong governance and the capacity and capability to deliver.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2015-06-22T15:07:31.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353912/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353912/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353912/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-12","Local Government: Devolution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what representations he has received from or on behalf of town and county authorities on his Department's policies on devolution.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","2303"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353913","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-22","<p>Government Ministers have set out the policy on devolution in public speeches and articles in the national press. Additionally, Ministers and officials are engaging with local authorities and Local Enterprise Partnerships across the country.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2015-06-22T15:09:05.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353913/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353913/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353913/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-12","Local Government: Devolution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to make town and county authorities aware of his Department's policies on devolution.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","2304"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353914","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-22","<p>My Department is encouraging town and county authorities to ensure that they benefit from devolution by bringing forward proposals that set out clearly how they will use greater powers and freedoms to maximise economic growth for their area.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2015-06-22T15:10:06.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353914/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353914/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353914/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-12","Local Government: Devolution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to ensure that the benefits of devolution reach town and county authority level.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","2305"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353915","Leader of the House","false","2015-06-17","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 15 June 2015 to Question UIN <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-06-10/1927/" target="_blank">1927</a></p>","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling","2290 ; 2291","2015-06-17T10:20:27.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353915/answer","Biography information for Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353915/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353915/answer",,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2015-06-12","Devolution: England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, with reference to page 24 of Implications for Devolution of England, Cm 8969, published in December 2014, when he plans that proposed arrangements for English votes for English laws will be put on a statutory footing.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","2308"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353916","Leader of the House","false","2015-06-17","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 15 June 2015 to Question UIN <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-06-10/1927/" target="_blank">1927</a></p>","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling","2291 ; 2308","2015-06-17T10:20:27.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353916/answer","Biography information for Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353916/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353916/answer",,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2015-06-12","Devolution: England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, if he will set out in his proposals for English votes for English laws whether only hon. Members for constituencies in England would be able to participate in (a) committee stages and (b) the committee of the whole House for bills with England-only implications.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","2290"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353917","Leader of the House","false","2015-06-17","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 15 June 2015 to Question UIN <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-06-10/1927/" target="_blank">1927</a></p>","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling","2290 ; 2308","2015-06-17T10:20:27.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353917/answer","Biography information for Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353917/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353917/answer",,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2015-06-12","Devolution: England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, what plans he has for public consultation in advance of decision of the House on proposals on English votes for English laws.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","2291"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353918","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-17","<p>The Government is currently considering applications for emergency authorisation of neonicotinoid seed treatments for use on oilseed rape. All applications are treated as commercially sensitive and therefore are not published.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-06-17T10:48:39.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353918/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353918/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353918/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-12","Neonicotinoids","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will publish the application made by the National Farmers Union for a derogation from restrictions on the use of neonicotinoids.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","2341"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353919","Department of Health","false","2015-06-19","<p>A wide range of research relating to stem cell transplantation is supported by the Department through the National Institute for Health Research (NIHR). The translation of scientific advances to the clinic is supported through NIHR Biomedical Research Centres and Units, clinical research facilities and experimental cancer medicine centres (funded jointly with Cancer Research UK). The NIHR clinical research network supports the coordination of clinical trials including any involving stem cell transplantation. NHS Blood and Transplant are directly involved in a number of research projects and provide an essential part of the necessary infrastructure supporting research in this field. NHS England supports the important role of innovation and research in transforming the quality of services.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-06-19T11:09:08.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353919/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353919/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353919/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-12","Stem Cells: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to support scientific research into stem cell transplantation.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","2328"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353920","Department of Health","false","2015-06-19","<p>NHS England expects to publish its response to the Investing in Specialised Services consultation by the end of June 2015.</p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-06-19T10:58:35.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353920/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353920/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353920/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-12","NHS England: Public Consultation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when he expects NHS England to respond to its consultation on Investing in Specialised Services.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","2329"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353921","Department of Health","false","2015-06-22","<p>Since 2011, the Department has provided our delivery partners, NHS Blood and Transplant and Anthony Nolan, a total of £16 million in additional, new funding to improve stem cell transplantation services in the United Kingdom. A further £3 million investment was announced in March 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This funding has led to a tangible improvement in the availability of stem cells in the UK and the achievements include:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>- More UK patients received a stem cell transplant in 2014 than ever before.</p><p> </p><p>- Over 60% of black, Asian and minority ethnic (BAME) patients are now able to find a well matched donor compared to only 40% in 2010.</p><p> </p><p>- A single unified bone marrow donor registry has been created streamlining the provision of stem cells and reducing the time to provide cells from adult donors.</p><p> </p><p>- The proportion of patients receiving cord blood from UK donors has significantly increased.</p><p> </p><p>- The increased use of UK-sourced stem cells has meant that more donors than ever are available to donate leading to a significant cost saving by reducing the need to import stem cells.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The report ‘Destination Cure – arriving at a better future’ from Anthony Nolan is a timely contribution to the debate on the future of this work.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-06-22T16:15:58.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353921/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353921/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353921/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-12","Haematological Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will make an assessment of the implications for his policies of the recommendations in the report, Destination: Cure - arriving at a better future for people with blood cancer by Anthony Nolan; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","2327"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353922","Department of Health","false","2015-06-16","<p>We will shortly publish a consultation on how best to implement these savings in ways that minimise any impact on front-line services.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","2161 ; 2219","2015-06-16T16:17:30.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353922/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353922/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353922/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-12","Public Health: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of recently announced changes to public health funding on public health initiatives on (a) exercise, (b) obesity, (c) smoking cessation and (d) sexual health.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","2363"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353923","Department for International Development","false","2015-06-19","<p>DFID published its management response to the Independent Commission for Aid Impact’s <em>Business in Development</em> report on 11 June. The management response sets out the eight actions DFID will take in response to ICAI’s findings on DFID’s work with the private sector, including our corporate partnerships.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>There are many ways in which DFID protects the livelihoods of small-scale farmers, for example by helping 6 million farmers in 40 countries across Asia and Africa adapt to climate change, securing the right to land and property for 5.8 million people (including 2.6 million women), and funding research into new technologies to increase productivity. We will make further programming decisions during the forthcoming spending review.</p>","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps",,"2015-06-19T12:40:41.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353923/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353923/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353923/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-06-12","Overseas Aid: Farmers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will make an assessment of the implications for her Department's policies on corporate partnerships of the findings of the report of the Independent Commission for Aid Impact, Business in Development, published in May 2015; and what steps she plans to take to ensure that UK aid protects the livelihoods of small-scale farmers.","false","Biography information for Ms Diane Abbott","Hackney North and Stoke Newington","Ms Diane Abbott","2367"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353924","Department for International Development","false","2015-06-19","<p>In the context of African food systems, DFID continually reviews the effectiveness of its relevant policy and programme work, some of which may involve multinational companies. DFID is focused on ensuring agricultural investments are responsible and benefit the poorest.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps",,"2015-06-19T12:38:47.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353924/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353924/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353924/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-06-12","Africa: Food","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if her Department will conduct an assessment of whether its strategy in working with multinational companies is effective in reducing poverty and improving the equity and sustainability of Africa's food systems.","false","Biography information for Ms Diane Abbott","Hackney North and Stoke Newington","Ms Diane Abbott","2299"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353925","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-22","<p>Following the discovery on 1 May of a mass grave in Thailand containing the bodies of Rohingya, and the ensuing humanitarian crisis at sea in South East Asia, the UK lobbied governments in the region to address the urgent humantarian needs of those stranded at sea. In particular, we urged countries in the region to uphold their obligation of rescue at sea for vessels in distress, and to take a coordinated approach to people trafficking.</p><p>On 18 May, I called the Burmese Ambassador to the Foreign and Commonwealth Office to press for an immediate humanitarian response and to urge Burma to take part in regional coordination efforts. On 20 May, I met the Bangladeshi Foreign Secretary to stress the need for Bangladesh to work within the region to address people trafficking and irregular migration originating from Bangladesh. Our officials have also discussed the issue with EU partners. Permanent Representatives in New York discussed the crisis in the UN Security Council on 28 May. While the immediate crisis is now receding, we are also pushing for a long term solution to the underlying problems, including the status of the Rohingya and an improvement to the dire socio-economic conditions faced by the Rohingya in Rakhine which is a key driver of their migration.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2015-06-22T11:34:41.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353925/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353925/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353925/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-12","Rohingya: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with international partners and his counterparts in South East Asia on (a) resolving the situation of Rohingya migrants and (b) ensuring that search and rescue operations take place in the Andaman Sea.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","2317"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353926","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-22","<p>The exact figure is unknown. From 8,000 migrants originally estimated to be at sea in late May, the latest figures from the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) indicate that around 1,200 to 1,300 remain unaccounted for. It is likely that some of these will have returned, while others may have disembarked without UNHCR or other authorities’ knowledge. We continue to monitor the situation closely and urge countries in the region not to turn away boats in distress.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2015-06-22T11:38:32.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353926/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353926/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353926/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-12","Rohingya: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent estimate his Department has made of the number Rohingya migrants from Burma adrift in the Andaman Sea.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","2318"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353927","Department for International Development","false","2015-06-19","<p>DFID works across government to contribute to the overall HMG response to these issues and works closely with international partners, including the World Bank and UN agencies. For example, DFID is helping shape the EU’s development spending to effectively address the root causes of migration across Africa and the Middle East. We are also providing technical expertise through the World Bank in Libya to contribute to the political settlement process and are leading the £125 million DFID funded Arab Partnership Economic Programme Facility (APEF). This programme - led by multilateral partners including the World Bank, European Bank for Reconstruction and Development, European Investment Bank and Islamic Development Bank – is helping build more inclusive economies and generate more jobs and opportunities across the region.</p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2015-06-19T12:40:21.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353927/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353927/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353927/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-06-12","Mediterranean Sea: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what plans her Department has to work with international partners to tackle (a) political instability in northern Africa, (b) criminal gangs which profit from human trafficking and (c) other underlying causes of the migrant situation in the Mediterranean.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","2320"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353928","Home Office","false","2015-06-23","<p>Initial medical triaging and assistance is carried out on board UK vessels deployed to the Mediterranean for search and rescue purposes. Migrants are then taken to a nearby port, as directed by the Italian authorities, where their needs can be more fully assessed and addressed by Italian authorities there.</p><p>The UK has regular discussions with other Member States about search and rescue in the Mediterranean.</p><p>Furthermore, the UK is also playing a leading role in pushing for comprehensive, long-term action through the EU and the UN to tackle the cause of illegal immigration and the organised trafficking gangs behind it, as well as increasing support and protection for those who need it North and East Africa. We are clear that the need to break the link between getting on a boat and achieving residence in Europe.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","2321","2015-06-23T15:33:31.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353928/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353928/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353928/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-12","Mediterranean Sea: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department is taking to support migrants and asylum seekers who (a) are children, (b) are elderly, (c) have serious injuries and (d) have other specialist needs who are rescued during operations in the Mediterranean.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","2319"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353929","Home Office","false","2015-06-23","<p>Initial medical triaging and assistance is carried out on board UK vessels deployed to the Mediterranean for search and rescue purposes. Migrants are then taken to a nearby port, as directed by the Italian authorities, where their needs can be more fully assessed and addressed by Italian authorities there.</p><p>The UK has regular discussions with other Member States about search and rescue in the Mediterranean.</p><p>Furthermore, the UK is also playing a leading role in pushing for comprehensive, long-term action through the EU and the UN to tackle the cause of illegal immigration and the organised trafficking gangs behind it, as well as increasing support and protection for those who need it North and East Africa. We are clear that the need to break the link between getting on a boat and achieving residence in Europe.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","2319","2015-06-23T15:33:31.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353929/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353929/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353929/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-12","Mediterranean Sea: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent discussions her Department has had with its EU counterparts on search and rescue operations in the Mediterranean.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","2321"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353930","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-17","<p>I have regular meetings with a number of stakeholders to discuss a wide range of issues affecting the rail industry, including Network Rail.</p>","Derbyshire Dales","Mr Patrick McLoughlin",,"2015-06-17T11:40:39.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353930/answer","Biography information for Sir Patrick McLoughlin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353930/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353930/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-12","Network Rail","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions he has had with (a) the Office of Rail Regulation, (b) the Department's Rail Executive and (c) other bodies on the future of Network Rail.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","2371"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353931","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-17","<p>The testing programme has demonstrated that the IEP train is capable of running at 125 miles per hour on diesel. Passengers can expect journey time improvements of circa 15 minutes on the routes served.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-06-17T11:44:20.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353931/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353931/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353931/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-12","Rolling Stock: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 9 June 2015 to Question 1261, whether bi-modal IEP trains running on diesel power will be capable of running at the maximum permitted linespeed of 125 miles per hour.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","2340"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353932","Department of Health","false","2015-06-22","<p>NHS England continues to expand the list of clinical indications for which proton beam therapy is most beneficial. It commissions independent evidence based reviews on specific diagnoses, which highlight either proof of principle for the use of protons, such as paediatric cancer, or where there is no evidence, such as prostate cancer.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The versions of three proton beam therapy policies that are out for consultation are available on the NHS England website, listed under the ‘Cancer’ section, at:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.engage.england.nhs.uk/consultation/specialised-services-consultation" target="_blank">www.engage.england.nhs.uk/consultation/specialised-services-consultation</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Each policy contains information on the evidence base.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-06-22T10:38:18.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353932/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353932/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353932/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-12","Radiotherapy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what peer-reviewed evidence NHS England has assessed to inform its decision on the use of proton beam therapy as a treatment for extracranial indications.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","2315"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353933","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-17","<p>Department for Transport officials have asked Southeastern to consider all available opportunities within the rolling stock market and received outline options in February, with a more detailed proposal due from Southeastern by the end of the month. Any decision on the Department funding additional rolling stock must be supported by a business case which clearly demonstrates both affordability and value for money, and we will be working closely with Southeastern to assess the options, costs and benefits before taking any funding decisions.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-06-17T11:25:47.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353933/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353933/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353933/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-12","South Eastern Trains: Rolling Stock","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he plans to allocate surplus Thameslink rolling stock to SouthEastern Trains in response to the submission made to his Department by SouthEastern in February 2015.","false","Biography information for Heidi Alexander","Lewisham East","Heidi Alexander","2338"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353934","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-23","<p>The Bradwell new build site identified in the National Policy Statement Nuclear as one of 8 sites potentially suitable for deployment of a new nuclear reactor by 2025 and is owned by EDF.</p><p>The development of the site is a commercial matter for EDF.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-06-23T13:23:37.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353934/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353934/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/353934/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-12","Nuclear Power Stations: Bradwell-on-sea","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, whether she plans to give the Bradwell nuclear site to (a) the Chinese State Nuclear Corporation or (b) another Chinese state-owned company in order to build a Chinese-manufactured reactor.","false","Biography information for Harry Harpham","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Harry Harpham","2307"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349888","Department for Education","false","2015-06-17","<p>The additional hours will be available to families where both parents are working, or the sole parent is working in a lone parent family. Further information on the detail of which parents will qualify will be announced in due course.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Parents who are in full time education are already able to access help with the costs of childcare. Full-time higher education students with children can apply for a Childcare Grant of:</p><p> </p><ul><li><p>up to £150.23 a week for 1 child;</p></li><li><p>up to £257.55 a week for 2 or more children.</p></li></ul><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The grant helps with childcare costs for children under-15, or under-17 if they have special educational needs.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Parents must be eligible for student finance to apply for a Childcare Grant. More information on the Childcare Grant can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/childcare-grant/overview" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/childcare-grant/overview</a></p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2015-06-17T14:05:21.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349888/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349888/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349888/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-11","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether it is her policy that families with parents in full-time further education will be eligible for 30 hours a week free childcare under the Government's new childcare proposals.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","2129"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349889","Department for Education","false","2015-06-17","<p>As I announced on Monday 15 June 2015, the department will be conducting a review of the cost of providing childcare. This will inform the cost of the new childcare entitlement of 30 hours for working families, which will be considered as part of the Budget and Spending Review process.</p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2015-06-17T14:16:54.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349889/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349889/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349889/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-11","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate she has made of the potential cost of the introduction of 30 hours a week free childcare.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","2132"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349890","Department for Education","false","2015-06-17","<p>The government is absolutely committed to supporting families with disabled children.</p><p> </p><p>We want every eligible parent that wants to take advantage of the new entitlement to be able to. That includes parents of children with disabilities, and therefore we will of course consider issues of funding and accessibility for those children.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The first part of this is our cross-government review of the cost of providing childcare, which will include a consideration of the costs for children with additional needs. A call for evidence to inform the review was launched on 15 June and will close on 10 August 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The call for evidence is available here: <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/cost-of-providing-childcare-review-call-for-evidence" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/consultations/cost-of-providing-childcare-review-call-for-evidence</a></p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2015-06-17T14:13:54.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349890/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349890/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349890/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-11","Children: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether her Department plans to include provisions in the Childcare Bill for extra funding for children currently in receipt of disability living allowance for children or enhanced child tax credits as a consequence of a disability.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","2133"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349891","Department for Education","false","2015-06-17","<p>The additional hours will be available to families where both parents are working or the sole parent is working in a lone parent family. More detail will be available in due course.</p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2015-06-17T14:11:02.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349891/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349891/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349891/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-11","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what eligibility provisions she plans to propose for children of families in which parents live apart or with different legal partners to be entitled to 30 hours a week free childcare under the Government's childcare proposals.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","2134"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349892","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-18","<p>Details about the role for employers in delivering Tax-Free Childcare can be found in Chapter 4 of ‘Delivering Tax-Free Childcare: the Government’s response to the consultation on design and operation’:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/318953/PU1607_Tax_free_Childcare_response.pdf</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2015-06-18T14:20:01.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349892/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349892/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349892/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-11","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what his policy is on the role employers play in the delivery of tax-free childcare.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","2144"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349893","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-16","<p>Whilst this is a commercial matter for the companies we continue to monitor the situation. We remain confident in the Hinkley Point C project – EDF plans for the power station to start producing low-carbon electricity from 2023.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-06-16T13:13:39.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349893/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349893/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349893/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-11","Hinkley Point C Power Station","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what recent assessment she has made of the financial position of (a) EDF Energy and (b) Areva in relation to their potential contribution to the construction and running of the planned nuclear power plant at Hinkley C.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","2130"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349894","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-16","<p>CICAIR Limited, the body designated to carry out the Secretary of State's executive and administrative functions in respect of approved inspectors, assesses the qualifications and experience of bodies applying to be approved inspectors and when re-approvals are made. It also carries out periodic audits of the general performance of approved inspectors. CICAIR also has processes in place to deal with complaints made against approved inspectors relating to performance on a particular job.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2015-06-16T15:57:18.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349894/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349894/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349894/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-11","Building Regulations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether independent oversight is in place to assure the day-to-day standard of work undertaken by approved inspectors of the compliance of new homes with building regulations.","false","Biography information for Mrs Maria Miller","Basingstoke","Mrs Maria Miller","2160"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349895","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-16","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2015-06-16T15:54:02.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349895/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349895/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349895/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-11","Building Regulations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many cases have been brought under section 35 of the Building Act 1984 in cases where new build homes contravene building regulations in the last 10 years; and how many such cases have resulted in the imposition of fines.","false","Biography information for Mrs Maria Miller","Basingstoke","Mrs Maria Miller","2208"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349896","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-16","<p>Local authorities are required under section 91 of the Building Act 1984 to provide a building control service in their own name. It is permissible for a local authority to sub-contract some aspects of provision of the service to outside bodies but not to delegate responsibility to provide a full service.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2015-06-16T15:55:02.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349896/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349896/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349896/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-11","Building Regulations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, which local authorities delegate in full the function of ensuring building regulation compliance to approved inspectors who are approved and monitored by the Construction Industry Council.","false","Biography information for Mrs Maria Miller","Basingstoke","Mrs Maria Miller","2209"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349897","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-16","<p>Where an approved inspector is the building control body it is required to send certain notices to the relant local authority. The local authority must keep these on a public reguister so they will be available to new home purchasers. However, there are no requirements for approved inspectors to make publicly available all the records of their checking activities.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2015-06-16T15:56:10.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349897/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349897/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/349897/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-11","Building Regulations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps are in place to enable new home purchasers to see the detailed records made by approved inspectors responsible for ensuring technical building regulation standards are met during the construction of a new home.","false","Biography information for Mrs Maria Miller","Basingstoke","Mrs Maria Miller","2217"
